LAGOS – Senator Anthony Adefuye, a chieftain of the All Progres­sives Congress (APC) has dismissed the claim by some Nigerians that Asiwaju Bola Tinubu, the party’s national leader will not get enough support from the Northern part of the country if he de­cides to contest in the 2023 presidential election. Speaking in an interview with Daily Independent on Tuesday, Adefuye who said Tinubu is a bridge builder whose influence cuts across all parts of the country said the former Lagos state gover­nor has more and friends and supporters in the Northern part of the country than the South. “Those saying Asiwaju will not get the support of northerners are wrong be­cause the man is even more popular and has many sup­porters in the North than in the South. He is the most influential politician in Nige­ria today. Even his northern friends have more access to him than those of us in the South here”. EXPOSED - HOW LAGOS DOCTOR DISCOVERED MAJOR REASONS WHY MOST WIVES NOW HEAVILY CHEATS ON THEIR HUSBANDS AND THE PERMANENT SECRET TO SEXUALLY SATISFYING THEIR WIVES. DON'T BE A VICTIM! Also speaking on the controversy trailing the zoning agreement in the APC, Adefuye, a member of Lagos Governor’s Advisory Council (GAC)said most po­litical parties in the country usually have a gentleman’s agreement that power should rotate between the North and South. He urged APC to re­spect the agreement. “The issue of the Presi­dency is an unwritten agree­ment; it rotates between the North and the South. Once a Northerner has been there for eight years max­imum, it must come down to the South. So, whoever is thinking that it is the North and is ambitious to become the President in 2023 is day­dreaming and wants to break Nigeria”. Zulum Offers Christmas Largesse To Soldiers Of 151 Battalion Jigawa Pays Over N19bn Pension Dues In Five Years He also said it is the turn of the South-West to produce the President of Nigeria in 2023 as the only region that is yet to do so since the return of democratic 